AGI -&nbsp;A Hong Kong court judged guilty of subversion > 14 pro-democracy activists in the most imposing process mounted against the opposition since China imposed a law on national security > to repress dissent.<br> I 14, together with 31 others who had declared themselves guilty of the opening of the proceedings, risk life >, even if the judgment is not expected shortly.b<r> The law imposed by Beijing in 2020 at the height of intense and sometimes violent protests in favour of democracy has allowed 47 people to be charged for subversion, accusing them of political activities aimed at bringing down the government.
<br> Sixteen defendants - including activists, former MPs and district councillors > - had proclaimed themselves not guilty and today Judge Andrew Chan declared guilty 14. Two former district councillors were judged not guilty.&nbsp; In the ruling the court states that the 14 had planned to undermine "the power and authority both of the government and of the head of the executive to create a constitutional crisis in Hong Kong".
&nbsp;
The trial took place without a jury and the judges were chosen by a pool of judges > personally selected by the leader of Hong Kong. The 31 who were guilty had done so hoping for judgments. Lawrence Lau, one of the defendants judged not guilty, has ensured that he will continue to support the rest of the group. "I hope everyone continues to worry about our friends involved in this case," he said.
&nbsp;
According to the accusation, the 47 defendants had conspired to subvert state power > organizing unofficial primary elections, as part of their plan to form a majority in the legislature in order to veto government budgets and force leadership to accept the demands made by protesters in 2019 and finally resign.&nbsp;
&nbsp; Defence lawyers > argued that Hong Kong's mini-constitution allowed such maneuvers and that the issue was "purely political rather than legal".
<br> But in his judgment the court stated that if the defendants agreed to put the veto "indiscriminately" to the budget in an attempt to force the government to adhere to their demands, "this would constitute an abuse of power".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<br> Outside the court the League of Social-Democrats - one of the last few voices of the opposition left in Hong Kong - attempted to organize a small protest. "We just want to express our opinion, I don't know why the police are hindering us: Hong Kong should continue to be a place with freedom of expression and reunion", said Chan Po-ying, who is also the wife of one of the defendants: Leung "Long Hair" Kwok-hung.
<br Also noted activist Alexandra Wong, also known as Grandma Wong, attempted to stage a protest before the police moved her across the street to a fenced area. "Free the 47 immediately!" cried, waving a British flag, "Support democracy, support the 47>!" The case was closely followed by the international community, with diplomats from the consulates of Great Britain, France, the European Union and Italy who presented themselves in the Tribunal.
<br> "The Government of the United Kingdom was clear in expressing our concern for the erosion of a significant political opposition in Hong Kong," said the British general consulate in a statement to AFP.&nbsp; In response to arrests in 2021, the United States sanctioned six Chinese and Hong Kong officials. Before today's ruling, 114 people had been judged guilty of crimes related to national security law, but the case against the group of 47 was the most bodily.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The Hong Kong Minister of Justice will appeal against the absolution of the two defendants>&nbsp;. "We want to inform the court that the secretary intends to appeal against the absolution of the two defendants," said Maggie Yang in court.
&nbsp;
<h2>China, enough interferences &nbsp;</h2>
China has asked critics abroad of Hong Kong's security laws to "stop interfering", on the day when the condemnation of several activists for "dispute" arrived.
&nbsp;
<h2>Ue, deep concern for activists
"The condemnation under the National Security Act (Nsl) of pro-democracy politicians and activists in the case commonly known as "Hong Kong 47" today marks a further deterioration of fundamental freedoms and democratic participation in Hong Kong. Of the 16 defendants who declared themselves not guilty, 14 were convicted." In a statement, the EU spokesman for Foreign Policy.
<br> "The defendants involved in the unofficial primary elections organized by the pro-democracy opposition in Hong Kong in July 2020 are affected by a peaceful political activity which should be legitimate in any political system that respects fundamental democratic principles. The EU is deeply concerned about the judicial process politically motivated against the 47 defenders of democracy, the prolonged preventive detention and the refusal of bail for most defendants, who undermine trust in the rule of law enshrined in the Basic Law of Hong Kong," the spokesman said.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>Amnesty, sentences to silence dissent
"The unprecedented mass condemnation of today is the most ruthless example of how Hong Kong's national security law is used as a weapon to silence dissent. It represents an almost total purge of political opposition and highlights the rapid disintegration of human rights in Hong Kong." This is Amnesty's comment published on X.
&nbsp;
<h2>Protects outside the Court of First Instance
The head of security of Hong Kong confirmed that several pro-democracy activists were arrested outside the court where 14 people were judged guilty of subversion in the largest case of the city under a national security law.<br> "Out of the court there were several people, who caused a disorder and led a disorderly conduct and were arrested," said the head of security Chris Tang,
